Episodes.Title: The Scottish
Episodes.Plot: The oddly blended Scottish Samoan Jackie Clarke talks whisky, frugality and emancipation with the PM, Don McGlashan and the leader of New Zealand's Official Russian Army. From the high country to the city of sails. New Zealand is as Scottish as they come.

Episodes.Title: The Germans
Episodes.Plot: Westie comedian Ewen Filmour finds out that his grand-folks were as Bohemian as he is, and that there is a reason why Kiwis are so fond of war, and that beer and sausage combination. Not to mention an explanation for our dry sense of humour.

Episodes.Title: The English
Episodes.Plot: Working class lad, actor / director Michael Hurst discovers how many things we have to thank (and blame) the English for. He explores exactly why we drove Minis, not Citroens, prefer rugby and fish and chips, and don't like underarm deodorant.

Episodes.Title: The Chinese
Episodes.Plot: Bernadine Lim takes her Malaysian Chinese heritage to the goldfields and market gardens. When did the lepers and butter pioneers turn into hiphop artists? Is there a Chinese All Black? Can we shout out 'Asians are cool'?

Episodes.Title: The Irish
Episodes.Plot: Actor and dancing start Theresa Healey sets out to explain why her Irish ancestors were blamed for bringing public drunkenness, religious violence, melancholy, prostitution and mental illness to New Zealand.

Episodes.Title: The Croatian Dalmatian
Episodes.Plot: All Black/croatian rugby star Frano Botica meets the wine pioneers, rock breakers and rock stars who have brought the Adriatic influence to New Zealand. Just what did those Maori wahine see in the guys wearing cravats?
